-<h1>AMR-Nexus One Health Backend — Rev 2 Architecture</h1>
-<blockquote>
-<p><strong>Mission</strong>: A production-ready surveillance platform for Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR) in Kenya, aligned with WHO GLASS, HL7 FHIR, and WOAH standards. This backend repository serves strictly as the Data Backbone and API Gateway.</p>
-</blockquote>
-<hr />
-<h2>1. Core Architecture (July 14, 2026 Revision 2)</h2>
-<p>The system is strictly divided into the internal API gateway (this repository) and external ML microservices (owned by the Data Science team).</p>
-
-<h3>Component A: Data Backbone (This Repository)</h3>
-<ul>
-  <li><strong>Role:</strong> Robust, "real-data ready" schema focused on Human + Poultry data unification. Serves as the central API gateway.</li>
-  <li><strong>Data Entities:</strong> <code>AMRRecord</code> (core), <code>Alert</code> (AI triggers), <code>Guidance</code> (LLM advisories), <code>GenomicSignal</code>.</li>
-  <li><strong>Ingestion:</strong> <code>POST /api/v1/backbone/ingest/whonet</code> with strict Pydantic validation and data cleaning pipeline (imputing <code>facility_type</code>, <code>sub_county</code>).</li>
-  <li><strong>Dashboard API:</strong> Surfaces high-level telemetry, aggregates, and alerts for the frontend UI.</li>
-</ul>
-
-<h3>Component B & C: ML Engine & LLM Advisory (External Microservices)</h3>
-<ul>
-  <li><strong>Role:</strong> Unsupervised hotspot detection, forecasting, and LLM Markdown generation.</li>
-  <li><strong>Decoupling:</strong> The AI/ML team reads from the PostgreSQL/Kafka instances, performs the heavy compute, and writes results (Alerts, Guidance) back into the database.</li>
-  <li><strong>Zero Local ML:</strong> This backend repository does not contain or execute any ML training, inference, or LLM logic.</li>
-</ul>
-
-<hr />
-<h2>2. Monorepo Structure & Separation of Labor</h2>
-<p>The repository has been restructured into a strict <strong>Monorepo</strong> to support the 16-person team. Strict boundaries prevent overlap between software engineers, data scientists, and frontend developers.</p>
-
